column1: #Text=So as an answer to the question , I would find it unlikely that such a behaviour would evolve , but it 's not known yet .
#Text=Ants generally avoided the peroxide if they were healthy , but in some circumstances might they try to build resistance against infection in advance ?
#Text=That said , there is a very interesting study about resin collection in ants .
#Text=They collect this even if not infected , and when you infect them , they do n't collect more of the resin than normal .
#Text=So basically it seems like they collect it in order to keep diseases out of the nest , so they stop the disease before it can actually infect them .
#Text=Are there plans to follow this research up ?
#Text=I first want to find out where they get it from in nature .
#Text=There might be many sources of medicine ( recent evidence suggests that tobacco plays a similar role for bumble bees ) .

#Text=Dalial Freitak , who is also on this paper is currently running tests with Ph.D. student Siiri Fuchs ( who is also on the paper ) with other substances to see if any have the same effect as H2O2 [ hydrogen peroxide ] .
#Text=Once the behaviour has been well described in this species of ant , I might do a comparison with other species .
#Text=For example , once we find the source of the medicine in nature ... would species without access to this source also have evolved the same behaviour in the lab ?
#Text=And if so ... where would they get it from ?
#Text=What other research are you working on right now ?
#Text=I still have some questions left unanswered from my Ph.D. work related to how ants recognize who is a friend and who is n't .
#Text=I also started collaborating with Prof. Michael Poulsen from the University of Copenhagen on immunity in fungus-growing termites , as well as their chemical recognition abilities .

#Text=Furthermore we 're working on social parasitism in wood-ants ( ants have lots of animals exploiting the nest for shelter and resources , which all somehow have to get in to the fortress without getting killed ) .
